Definition 4.3. We say that an $X$-morphism $f:A\rightarrow B\otimes X$ is $X$-polar decomposable if there exists an $X$-positive morphism $g:A\rightarrow X\otimes A$ and an $X$-isometry $\mathcal{V}:X\otimes A\rightarrow B$ such that $f=\mathcal{V}_{\delta}\circ g$ i.e. $f$ can be depicted as $A$$\delta$$B$$X$$A$$g$$\mathcal{V}$
Definition 4.5. [POVM] Let $\langle X,\delta,\epsilon\rangle$ be a classical object. A POVM on a system of type $A$ which produces outcomes in $X$ is a morphism $\delta$$\delta$$X$$X$$f$$f$$A$$A$$A$$A$ where $f\in{\bf C}(A,X\otimes A)$ is $X$-polar-decomposable and such that $f^{\dagger}\circ f=1_{A}$.
Definition 4.1. An $X$-isometry is a morphism $\mathcal{V}:X\otimes A\rightarrow B$ for which $\mathcal{V}_{\delta}:=(1_{X}\otimes\mathcal{V})\circ(\delta\otimes 1_{A}):X% \otimes A\rightarrow X\otimes B$ is an isometry i.e. it satisfies $\mathcal{V}_{\delta}^{\dagger}\circ\mathcal{V}_{\delta}=1_{X\otimes A}\,.$
Definition 4.4. An $X$-scalar is a morphism $f:I\rightarrow X$. An $X$-scalar $t:I\rightarrow X$ is an $X$-inverse of $s:I\rightarrow X$ iff, setting $\lambda_{I}:I\simeq I\otimes I$, we have $\delta^{\dagger}\circ(s\otimes t)\circ\lambda_{I}=\epsilon^{\dagger}\,.$
Definition 4.2. A morphism $f:A\rightarrow A\otimes X$ is $X$-positive if there exists an $X$-morphism $g:B\rightarrow A\otimes X$ such that $\delta$$X$$f$$A$$X$$A$=$g$$A$$A$$X$$B$$g$$X$ In the second picture, the fact that the trapezoid on the left points with its sharp corner to the left, as compared to trapezoid on the right of which the sharp corner points to the right, indicates that it is “dagger’d” as compared to the one on the right. This graphical convention will be reused in what follows.
Definition 5.1. We define $\omega:(\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D})^{op}\longrightarrow Sets$ by $\omega(n)=\mathfrak{D}_{n},\,\ \text{for each}\,\ n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}.$
Definition 2.3. Let $(P,\leqslant)$ be a partially ordered set and $M\subseteq P$. We say that $M$ is an up-set if for each $x\in M$ and $y\in P$ we have $x\leqslant y$ implies $y\in M$. Similarly, $M$ is called a down-set if for each $x\in M$ and $y\in P$ we have $y\leqslant x$ implies $y\in M$. Given an element $x\in P$, we define the up-set and down-set generated by $x$ by $\uparrow x=\{y\in P:x\leqslant y\}$ and $\downarrow x=\{y\in P:y\leqslant x\}$, respectively. We can also define the up-set generated by a subset $M$ of $P$ by$\uparrow M=\{x\in P:m\leqslant x\,\ \text{for some}\,\ m\in M\}=\bigcup_{m\in M% }\uparrow m$, and similarly, we define the down-set generated by $M$ by $\downarrow M=\bigcup_{m\in M}\downarrow m$. We denote the collection of all up-sets of a partially ordered set $P$ by $\mathcal{U}(P)$ and the set of all down-sets by $\mathcal{D}(P)$.
Definition 4.4. A pair $(\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D},J)$, where $J$ is a Grothendieck topology on $\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D}$, is called a site.
Definition 4.2. A Grothendieck topology on the category $\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D}$ is a function $J$ which assigns to each object $n$ of $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ a collection $J(n)$ of sieves on $\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D}$, in such a way that (i) the maximal sieve $\mathfrak{D}_{n}$ (the set of all divisors of $n$) is in $J(n)$; (ii) (stability axiom) if $S\in J(n)$ and $k\leqslant n$ then $S\cap\mathfrak{D}_{k}$ is in $J(k)$; (iii) (transitivity axiom) if $S\in J(n)$ and $R$ is any sieve on $n$ such that $R\cap\mathfrak{D}_{k}$ is in $J(k)$ for each $k\in S$, then $R\in J(n)$.
Definition 4.5. Let $F:(\mathbb{Z}^{+}_{D})^{op}\longrightarrow Sets$ be a functor (a contravariant functor to Sets is also called a presheaf ). Let $n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ and $S\in J(n)$. Then a family $\left\langle a_{k}\right\rangle_{k\in S}$ in $\prod_{k\in S}F(k)$ is called a matching family for the cover $S$ with elements of $F$ if $F(a_{k})=a_{t}$ for each $k,t\in S$ such that $t\leqslant k$. An element $a\in F(n)$ such that $F(a)=a_{k}$ for each $k\in S$ is called an amalgamation. We say that $F$ is a $J$-sheaf if for each $n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, for each $S\in J(n)$ and for each matching family $\left\langle a_{k}\right\rangle_{k\in S}$ there is a unique amalgamation $a\in F(n)$.
Definition 4.1. Given an element $k$ in $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, a subset $S$ of $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ is called a sieve on $k$ if $S\in\mathcal{D}(\mathfrak{D}_{k})$.
Definition 2.1. The multiplicative partial ordering on $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ is defined as follows: for all $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, $a\prec b$ if and only if there exists $c\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ such that $a=bc$.
Definition 2.2. The divisibility partial ordering on $\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ is defined as follows: for all $k,n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$, $k\leqslant n$ if and only if there exists $t\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$ such that $n=kt$.
Definition 1.9. [eo] A module category ${\mathcal{M}}$ over a finite tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is exact if it is finite and for any projective $P\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and any $M\in{\mathcal{M}}$, $P{\otimes}M$ is projective in ${\mathcal{M}}$.
Definition 1.2. We shall say that $K$ is $H$-simple from the left, (resp. $H$-simple from the right, resp. $H$-simple) if $K$ has no non-trivial left (resp. right, resp. two-sided) $H$-ideal. We shall say that $K$ is $H$-indecomposable if there are no nontrivial two-sided $H$-ideals $I$ and $J$ such that $K=I\oplus J$.
Definition 1.7. [eo] Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a ${\Bbbk}$-linear category. We shall say that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is finite if • it has finitely many simple objects; • each simple object $X$ has a projective cover $P(X)$; • the $\operatorname{Hom}$ spaces are finite-dimensional; • each object has finite length. A finite tensor category is a tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ such that the underlying abelian category is finite and the unit object ${\mathbf{1}}$ is simple.
Definition 1.8. A fusion category is a finite tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ such that the underlying abelian category is semisimple.
Definition 1.22. An equivariant $(S,R)$-bimodule is a $(S,R)$-bimodule $P$ provided with a left coaction $\lambda:P\to H{\otimes}_{{\Bbbk}}P$ that is a morphism of $(S,R)$-bimodules. Morphisms of equivariant bimodules are defined in the obvious way. The category of equivariant bimodules is denoted ${}_{S}^{H}{\mathcal{M}}_{K}$.
Definition 1.13. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be a finite module category over ${\mathcal{C}}$. Let $M_{1},M_{2}\in{\mathcal{M}}$. Then the functor $X\mapsto\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{M}}}(X{\otimes}M_{1},M_{2})$ is representable and an object $\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}(M_{1},M_{2})$ representing this functor is called the internal Hom of $M_{1}$ and $M_{2}$. See [eo, O1] for details. Thus $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{M}}}(X{\otimes}M_{1},M_{2})\simeq\operatorname{% Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(X,\underline{\operatorname{Hom}}(M_{1},M_{2}))$ for any $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$, $M_{1},M_{2}\in{\mathcal{M}}$.
Definition 2.23. ($\operatorname{Mod}^{\text{st}}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$) The category $\operatorname{Mod}^{\text{st}}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$ of strict morphisms is the subcategory $Z^{0}(\operatorname{Mod}_{\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A}))\subseteq\operatorname{Mod}_% {\text{dg}}(\mathcal{A})$. The identity $[d,\varphi]=0$ is equivalent to the conditions that • $\varphi(m\cdot a)=\varphi(m)\cdot a$, and • $d^{\prime}\varphi(m)=\varphi(dm)$.
Definition 2.2. (morphisms) Morphisms are graded $\operatorname{Hom}^{\Gamma}_{S}(M,N)=\bigoplus_{j\in\Gamma}\operatorname{Hom}^% {j}_{S}(M,N)=\bigoplus_{j\in\Gamma}\prod_{i\in\Gamma}\operatorname{Hom}_{S}(M^% {i},N^{i+j}).$
Definition 2.16. (strict morphisms) A strict morphism of strictly unital right modules over an $A_{\infty}$-algebra $(M,b^{M}_{\bullet})\to(M^{\prime},b^{M^{\prime}}_{\bullet})$ is a closed degree $0$ morphism whose only non-zero element is “linear”: $\phi_{\bullet}=\phi_{1}\in\operatorname{Hom}^{0}_{S}(M,M^{\prime})\cap Z^{0}(% \operatorname{Mod}_{\infty}(M,M^{\prime})).$
Definition 3.1. ($U(A)$) The enveloping algebra $U(A)$ is a curved dg-algebra obtained by setting $X=((A[1])^{\otimes\geq 1})[-1]$ and $U(A)=X^{\mathchoice{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes% $}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}}.$ It is equipped with the derivation $d=d_{1}+\overline{d}_{2}$ whose value on generators is $D=D_{1}+\overline{D}_{2}$ for • $D_{1}=-\omega\circ B\circ\sigma,$ and • $\overline{D}_{2}=-\omega^{{\mathchoice{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{% \scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}}2}% \circ\overline{\Delta}\circ\sigma$ where $\overline{\Delta}$ is the comultiplication on reduced tensor coalgebra $(A[1])^{\otimes\geq 1}$. This means $\overline{\Delta}(\sigma(a_{1})\otimes\dotsm\otimes\sigma(a_{\ell}))=\sum_{i=1% }^{\ell-1}\sigma(a_{1})\otimes\dotsm\otimes\sigma(a_{i}){\mathchoice{\mbox{% \scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$% }}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}}\sigma(a_{i+1})\otimes\dotsm\otimes\sigma(a_{\ell}).$ Equivalently, $\overline{\Delta}=\Delta-\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}{\mathchoice{\mbox{\scriptsize$% \boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{% \tiny$\boxtimes$}}}1_{\otimes}-1_{\otimes}{\mathchoice{\mbox{\scriptsize$% \boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\scriptsize$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{\tiny$\boxtimes$}}{\mbox{% \tiny$\boxtimes$}}}\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}$ were $\Delta$ is the comultiplication on full tensor coalgebra $(A[1])^{\otimes}$.
Definition 2.13. (strictly unital right module) A strictly unital right module over a strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebra is an $S$-module $M$ and a map $b^{M}_{\bullet}=\sum_{\ell=0}^{\infty}b^{M}_{\ell}\in\operatorname{Hom}^{0}_{S% }(M\odot(A[1])^{\otimes},M)$ such that $(B^{M})^{2}=0$ for $B^{M}=b_{\bullet}^{M}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}+\mathbf{1}\odot\mathbf{1}^{% \otimes}\otimes b_{\bullet}\otimes\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}$. In addition, • $-b_{2}^{M}(\mathbf{1}\odot\eta)=\mathbf{1}$, and • $b^{M}_{\ell}(\mathbf{1}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\otimes\eta\otimes\mathbf{1}^{% \otimes})=0$ for $\ell\neq 2.$
Definition 2.4. (geometric series) We make the notation $M^{\otimes}=\bigoplus_{\ell=0}^{\infty}M^{\otimes\ell},$ where $M^{\otimes\ell}=\underbrace{M\otimes\dotsm\otimes M}_{\text{$\ell$ copies}}$ and $M^{\otimes 0}=S\cdot 1_{\otimes}$ for a symbol $1_{\otimes}$. We also write $M^{\otimes\geq 1}$ for $\bigoplus_{\ell=1}^{\infty}M^{\otimes\ell}$. A similar notation is used for morphisms. Given $\phi_{\bullet}\colon M^{\otimes}\to N,$ we write $(\phi_{\bullet})^{\otimes}=\sum_{\ell=0}^{\infty}(\phi_{\bullet})^{\otimes\ell% }\colon M^{\otimes}\to N^{\otimes}$ where $(\phi_{\bullet})^{\otimes\ell}=\sum_{i_{1},\dotsm,i_{\ell}}\phi_{i_{1}}\otimes% \dotsm\otimes\phi_{i_{\ell}}.$ We also make use of the “extension by zero” convention for direct sums: for a map $\psi$ on a summand of a direct sum, we extend it to the entire direct sum by first projecting onto the summand in question.
Definition 2.1. (modules) Usual conventions for modules include: • as a module, $S$ is concentrated in degree $0$, • the degree of a homogeneous element $m$ is written $|m|\in\Gamma,$ • a homogeneous element $m$ has a sign $(-1)^{|m|}\in\{\pm 1\}$ (when it is unambiguous, simply $(-1)^{m}$ ), • a shift functor $M[1]^{i}=M^{i+1},$ • and an $S$-module isomorphism $\sigma\colon M\to M[1]$ identifying $M^{i}$ with $M[1]^{i-1}$ and whose inverse is denoted $\omega.$
Definition 2.19. (curved dg-algebra) A curved dg-algebra $(\mathcal{A},d,c)$ is an $A_{\infty}$-algebra $\mathfrak{m}_{\bullet}\colon\mathcal{A}^{\diamond}\to\mathcal{A}$ with $\mathfrak{m}_{\ell}=0$ for all $\ell\geq 3.$ Notationally, we write • multiplication by $a\cdot a^{\prime}=\mathfrak{m}_{2}(a\diamond a^{\prime})$ (or concatenation), • the derivation3The derivation is called the “differential” despite the fact that it may not satisfy $d^{2}=0$. by $da=\mathfrak{m}_{1}(a)$, and • the curvature by $c=m_{0}(1)$, and the $A_{\infty}$-equations are exactly the conditions that • $dc=0$, • $d^{2}a=[c,a]=ca-ac$, • $d(a\cdot a^{\prime})=(da)\cdot a^{\prime}+(-1)^{a}a\cdot(da^{\prime}),$ and • $(a\cdot a^{\prime})\cdot a^{\prime\prime}=a\cdot(a^{\prime}\cdot a^{\prime% \prime})$. In addition, a strict unit $\eta$ defines an identity element $e=\omega(\eta)\in\mathcal{A}$ which is closed $de=0.$
Definition 2.24. ($\infty$-bimodule) An $A$-$A^{\prime}$-bimodule $V$ for curved $A_{\infty}$-algebras $A$ and $A^{\prime}$ is an $S$-module and a map $b^{V}_{\bullet,\bullet}\colon A[1]^{\otimes}\odot V\odot(A^{\prime})[1]^{% \otimes}\to V$ such that $(B^{V})^{2}=0$ for $B^{V}=B\odot\mathbf{1}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}+\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\odot b^{V% }_{\bullet,\bullet}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}+\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\odot\mathbf{% 1}\odot B^{\prime}.$ The $A_{\infty}$-equation for such a map is $b^{V}_{\bullet,\bullet}(B\odot\mathbf{1}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}+\mathbf{1}^{% \otimes}\odot b^{V}_{\bullet,\bullet}\odot\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}+\mathbf{1}^{% \otimes}\odot\mathbf{1}\odot B^{\prime})=0.$ If $A$ and $A^{\prime}$ are strictly unital, then $V$ is called strictly unital if $b^{V}_{\bullet,\bullet}(\sigma(a_{1})\otimes\dotsm\otimes\sigma(a_{k})\odot v% \odot\sigma(a^{\prime}_{1})\otimes\dotsm\otimes\sigma(a^{\prime}_{k^{\prime}})% )=0$ when $k+1+k^{\prime}>2$ and any $a_{i}=e$ or $a^{\prime}_{i^{\prime}}=e^{\prime}$.
Definition 2.11. (morphism of strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebras) A morphism of strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebras $(A,b_{\bullet})\to(A^{\prime},b^{\prime}_{\bullet})$ is an element $f_{\bullet}=\sum_{\ell=1}^{\infty}f_{\ell}\in\operatorname{Hom}^{0}_{S}((A[1])% ^{\otimes\geq 1},A^{\prime}[1])$ such that • $0=B^{\prime}F-FB\colon(A[1])^{\otimes}\to(A^{\prime}[1])^{\otimes}$ for $F=(f_{\bullet})^{\otimes}$, • $f_{1}(\eta)=\eta^{\prime}$, and • $f_{\ell}(\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\otimes\eta\otimes\mathbf{1}^{\otimes})=0$ for $\ell\neq 1$.
Definition 2.8. (strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-algebra) An $A_{\infty}$-algebra is an $S$-module $A$ and a map $b_{\bullet}=\sum_{\ell=0}^{\infty}b_{\ell}\in\operatorname{Hom}^{1}_{S}((A[1])% ^{\otimes},A[1]).$ such that $B^{2}=0$ for $B=\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\otimes b_{\bullet}\otimes\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}.$ An element $e\in A^{0}$ is called a strict unit if for $\eta=\sigma(e)$ • $b_{2}(\eta\otimes\mathbf{1})=-b_{2}(\mathbf{1}\otimes\eta)=\mathbf{1}$, and • $b_{\ell}(\mathbf{1}^{\otimes}\otimes\eta\otimes\mathbf{1}^{\otimes})=0$ for $\ell\neq 2.$ Such an element is unique if it exists.
